# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: windows-services
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:windows-services/background-process] A **background process** is a computer process that runs *behind the scenes* (i.e., in the background) and without user intervention.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Typical tasks for these processes include logging, system monitoring, scheduling, and user notification.
[src:windows-services/background-process] On a Windows system, a background process is either a computer program that does not create a user interface, or a Windows service.
[src:windows-services/background-process] The former are started just as any other program is started, e.g., via Start menu.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Windows services, on the other hand, are started by Service Control Manager.
[src:windows-services/background-process] In Windows Vista and later, they are run in a separate session.
[src:windows-services/background-process] On a Unix-like system, a daemon would be a background process.
[src:windows-services/background-process] However, in a shell that supports job control, a process that is in a process group whose process group ID differs from its terminal group ID (TGID) would be a background process.
[src:windows-services/background-process] (The TGID of a process is the process ID of the process group leader that opened the terminal, which is typically the login shell.
[src:windows-services/background-process] The TGID identifies the control terminal of the process group.) This type of process is unable to receive keyboard signals from its parent terminal, and typically will not send output to that terminal.
[src:windows-services/background-process] This more technical definition does not distinguish between whether or not the process can receive user intervention.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Although background processes are typically used for purposes needing few resources, any process can be run in the background, and such a process will behave like any other process, with the exceptions given above.
[src:windows-services/background-process] In Windows NT family of operating systems, a Windows service is a dedicated background process.
[src:windows-services/background-process] A Windows service must conform to the interface rules and protocols of the Service Control Manager, the component responsible for managing Windows services.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Windows services can be configured to start when the operating system starts, and to run in the background as long as Windows runs.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Alternatively, they can be started manually or by an event.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Windows NT operating systems include numerous services which run in context of three user accounts: `System`, `Network Service` and `Local Service`.
[src:windows-services/background-process] These Windows components are often associated with Host Process for Windows Services: svchost.exe.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Since Windows services operate in the context of their own dedicated user accounts, they can operate when a user is not logged on.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Before Windows Vista, services installed as "interactive services" could interact with Windows desktop and show a graphical user interface.
[src:windows-services/background-process] With Windows Vista, however, interactive services became deprecated and ceased operating properly, as a result of Windows Service Hardening.
[src:windows-services/background-process] A daemon is a type of background process designed to run continually in the background, waiting for event(s) to occur or condition(s) to be met.
[src:windows-services/background-process] When launched with the *daemon* function, daemons are disassociated from their parent terminal.
[src:windows-services/background-process] From a Unix command line, a background process can be launched using the "&" operator.
[src:windows-services/background-process] The *bg* command can resume a suspended job (sending SIGCONT), running it in the background.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Using the *fg* command will also set the foreground process group of the controlling terminal of the session to the process group of the job, bringing the job into the foreground.
[src:windows-services/background-process] The *jobs* command will list all processes associated with the current terminal and can be used to bring background processes into the foreground.
[src:windows-services/background-process] When a login session ends, via explicit logout or network disconnection, all processes, including background processes, will by default be terminated, to prevent them from becoming orphan processes.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Concretely, when the user exits the launching shell process, as part of shutdown it sends a *hangup* signal (SIGHUP) to all its jobs, to terminate all the processes in the corresponding process group.
[src:windows-services/background-process] To have processes continue to run, one can either not end the session, or end the session without terminating the processes.
[src:windows-services/background-process] A terminal multiplexer can be used to leave a session running but detach a virtual terminal from it, leaving processes running as child processes of the session; the user can then reattach session later.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Or, termination can be prevented by either starting the process via the nohup command (telling the process to ignore SIGHUP), or by subsequently running `disown` with the job id, which either removes the job from the job list entirely, or simply prevents SIGHUP from being sent.
[src:windows-services/background-process] In this example running on Unix, the *sleep* utility was launched into the background.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Afterward, the *ps* tool was run in the foreground, where it output the below text.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Many newer versions of smartphone and PDA operating systems now include the ability to start background processes.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Due to hardware limits, background processes on mobile operating systems are often restricted to certain tasks or consumption levels.
[src:windows-services/background-process] On Android, CPU use for background processes may be bounded at 5–10%.
[src:windows-services/background-process] Applications on Apple's iOS are limited to a subset of functions while running in the background.
[src:windows-services/background-process] On both iOS and Android, background processes, as well as background or unused apps, can be killed by the system if they are using too much memory or too much battery power.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In computing, a **daemon** is a program that runs as a background process, rather than being under the direct control of an interactive user.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Customary convention is to name a daemon process with the letter *d* as a suffix to indicate that it's a daemon.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] For example, syslogd is a daemon that implements system logging facility, and sshd is a daemon that serves incoming SSH connections.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Even though the concept can apply to many computing systems, the term *daemon* is used almost exclusively in the context of Unix-based systems.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In other contexts, different terms are used for the same concept.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Systems often start daemons at boot time that will respond to network requests, hardware activity, or other programs by performing some task.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Daemons such as cron may also perform defined tasks at scheduled times.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In the context of computing, the word is generally pronounced either as /ˈdiːmən/ *DEE-mən* or /ˈdeɪmən/ *DAY-mən*.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The term was coined by the programmers at MIT's Project MAC.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Unix systems inherited this terminology.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Maxwell's demon is consistent with Greek mythology's interpretation of a daemon as a supernatural being working in the background.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In the general sense, daemon is an older form of the word "demon", from the Greek δαίμων.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Alternative terms include *service* (used in Windows, from Windows NT onwards, and later also in Linux), *started task* (IBM z/OS), and *ghost job* (XDS UTS).
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Sometimes the more general term *server* or *server process* is used, particularly for daemons that operate as part of client-server systems.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] A daemon that connects to a computer network is a network service.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] After the term was adopted for computer use, it was incorrectly rationalized as a backronym for **d**isk **a**nd **e**xecution **mon**itor.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In a Unix-like system, the parent process of a daemon is often, but not always, the init process.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] A daemon is usually created either by the init process directly launching the daemon, by the daemon being run by an initialization script run by init, or by the daemon being launched by a super-server launched by init.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The init process in Research Unix and BSD starts daemons from an initialization script.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] A daemon started as a command in an initialization script must either fork a child process and then immediately exit, or must be run as a background process using &, so that the shell running the initialization script can continue after starting the daemon.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In the former case, the daemon process run from the shell exits, thus causing init to adopt the child process that runs as the daemon; in the latter case, when the shell running the initialization script exits, the child daemon process is adopted by init.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The versions of init in System III and in System V can run arbitrary commands and can be configured to run them once or to restart them when they terminate.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The former mechanism can be used to run initialization scripts; daemons started from those scripts behave the same as in Research Unix and BSD.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The latter mechanism can be used to run daemons directly from init.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] A daemon can also be launched from a user's command line.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] However, daemons launched in that fashion typically must perform other operations, such as dissociating the process from any controlling terminal (tty).
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Such procedures are often implemented in various convenience routines such as *daemon(3)*.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] A daemon launched by an initialization script need not do these steps, but doing so allows the daemon to be restarted by a user if it exits; init itself would not restart them.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In MS-DOS, daemon-like functionality was implemented as a terminate-and-stay-resident program (TSR).
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In Windows, a Windows service provides the functionality of a daemon.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] It runs as a process, usually does not interact with the user (i.e. via monitor, keyboard, or mouse) and may be launched by the operating system at boot time.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In Windows 2000 and later versions, a Windows service is configured and controlled via various interfaces including the Control Panel, the Service Control Manager `sc` command, the `net start` and `net stop` commands, PowerShell, or a custom program.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] However, any Windows application can perform the role of a daemon, not just a service, and some Windows daemons have the option of running as a normal process.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] In classic Mac OS, optional features and services were provided by system extensions and control panels – files loaded at startup time that patched the operating system.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] Later versions of classic Mac OS augmented these with faceless background applications: regular applications that ran in the background.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] To the user, these were still described as regular system extensions.
[src:windows-services/daemon-computing] The more modern macOS, which is Unix-based, uses daemons but uses the term "services" to designate software that performs functions selected from the Services menu, rather than using that term for daemons, as Windows does.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] The SCM executable, `Services.exe`, runs as a Windows console program and is launched by the Wininit process early during the system startup.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Its main function, `SvcCtrlMain()`, launches all the services configured for automatic startup.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Then a named pipe `\Pipe\Ntsvcs` is created as a remote procedure call interface between the SCM and the SCPs (Service Control Processes) that interact with specific services.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Next, it calls the `ScAutoStartServices()` function which loops through all the services marked as auto-start, paying attention to the calculated load-order dependencies.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] In case of a circular dependency an error is noted and the service depending on a service that belongs to a group coming later in the load order is skipped.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] For delayed auto-start services, grouping has no effect, and those are loaded at a later stage of system startup.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] For each service it wants to start, the SCM calls the `ScStartService()` function which checks the name of the file that runs the service's process, ensuring that the account specified for the service is same as the account that the service process runs in.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Next, the `ScLogonAndStartImage()` function is called for every service whose service process has not been already launched.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Service processes are created in a suspended state via the `CreateProcessAsUser()` API.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Before the service process' execution is resumed, a named pipe `\Pipe\Net\NtControlPipeX` (where X is a number incremented for each service iteration) is created which serves as a communication channel between the SCM and the service process.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Service process connects to the pipe by calling the `StartServiceCtrlDispatcher()` function, after which the SCM sends the service a "start" command.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Delayed auto-start services have been added in Windows Vista, in order to solve the problem of a prolonged system startup, as well as to speed-up the start of critical services that cannot be delayed.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Originally the auto-start method of service initialization was designed for essential system services upon which other applications and services depend.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] The SCM initializes the delayed services only after handling all the non-delayed auto-start services, by invoking the `ScInitDelayStart()` function.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] This function queues a delayed (120 seconds by default) work item associated with a corresponding worker thread.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] Other than being initialized after a delay, there are no other differences between delayed and non-delayed services.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] For that purpose, the `NtLoadDriver` system call is invoked, and the `SeLoadDriverPrivilege` is added to the SCM's process.
[src:windows-services/service-control-manager] SCM provides an additional functionality completely unrelated to Windows services: it notifies GUI applications such as the Windows Explorer when a network drive-letter connection has been created or deleted, by broadcasting Windows messages `WM_DEVICECHANGE`.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The svchost process was introduced in Windows 2000, although the underlying support for shared service processes has existed since Windows NT 3.1.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Its executable image, `%SystemRoot%\System32\Svchost.exe` or `%SystemRoot%\SysWOW64\Svchost.exe` (for 32-bit services running on 64-bit systems) runs in multiple instances, each hosting one or more services.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Services running in SvcHost are implemented as dynamically-linked libraries (DLLs).
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Each service's registry key must have a value named ServiceDll under the Parameters subkey, pointing to the respective service's DLL file.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Their ImagePath definition is of the form `%SystemRoot%\System32\svchost.exe -k %service group%`; (i.e. netsvcs).
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Services sharing the same SvcHost process specify the same parameter, having a single entry in the SCM's database.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The first time that a SvcHost process is launched with a specific parameter, it looks for a value of the same name under the `HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Svchost` key, which it interprets as a list of service names.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Then it notifies the SCM of all the services that it hosts.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] SCM does not launch a second SvcHost process for any of those received services; instead, it simply sends a "start" command to the respective SvcHost process containing the name of the service that should be launched within its context, and whose respective DLL SvcHost loads.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] According to a 2003 Microsoft presentation, the minimum working set of a shared service is approximately 150 KB instead of 800 KB for a standalone process.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Starting with Windows 10 version 1703, Microsoft changed the way services are grouped into host processes.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] On client computer systems with more than 3.5 GB of memory, services are no longer grouped into shared host processes.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Instead, each service is run in its own process.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] This results in better isolation of services, making the computer system more resilient to service failures and vulnerabilities and easier to debug.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Starting with Windows Vista, the internal identification of services inside shared processes (svchost included) is achieved by so-called service tags.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The service tag for each thread is stored in the SubProcessTag of its thread environment block (TEB).
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The tag is propagated across all threads that a main service thread subsequently starts, except for threads created indirectly by Windows thread-pool APIs.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The set of service tag management routines is currently an undocumented API, although it is used by some Windows utilities like netstat to display the TCP connections associated with each service.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Some third-party tools like ScTagQuery also make use of this API.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] In Windows XP and later editions, the command `tasklist /svc` shows a list of the services being run by each listed process (i.e. by each running instance of svchost.exe), with each separate instance of the svchost process identified by a unique Process ID number (PID).
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] In Windows 8, the Task Manager interface was streamlined so that each svchost entry can be expanded by a single click to a sub-list of services running inside it.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The Sysinternals Process Explorer (available as a free download from Microsoft) provides additional information about services running under svchost.exe processes, when the user hovers the mouse over an svchost instance in Process Explorer.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] None of the above methods allows the user to identify which of the multiple services running inside an svchost instance accesses a particular resource, i.e. processor, disk, network or memory; the Windows Resource Monitor only accounts for (most of) those resources at process level.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] It does however show processor usage at service level, on the "CPU" tab.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] A service-aware list of TCP connections and UDP ports opened can be obtained using the command `netstat -b`.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] In order to troubleshoot other kinds of problems with a service running inside an svchost instance, the service(s) suspected to be causing the problem must (all) be reconfigured so that each runs inside its own svchost instance.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] For example, `sc config foo type= own` will reconfigure the service named "foo" to run in its own svchost instance.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] Changing the type back to shared is done by an analogous command.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The service must be restarted for such a configuration change to take effect.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] This debugging process is not foolproof however; in some cases, a heisenbug may occur, which causes the problem to go away when the service is running separately.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] A more complex method of troubleshooting is to create an isolated service group.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] In Windows 10, starting with release 1703, svchost was redesigned by Microsoft to host only one service per process, depending on available system memory.
[src:windows-services/svchost-exe] The default setting causes services to be hosted independently if the system has at least 3.5 GB of RAM.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] In Windows NT operating systems, a **Windows service** is a computer program that operates in the background.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] It is similar in concept to a Unix daemon.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] It is the Services and Controller app, services.exe, that launches all the services and manages their actions, such as start, end, etc.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Windows services can be configured to start when the operating system is started and run in the background as long as Windows is running.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Windows NT operating systems include numerous services which run in context of three user accounts: System, Network Service and Local Service.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] These Windows components are often associated with Host Process for Windows Services.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Because Windows services operate in the context of their own dedicated user accounts, they can operate when a user is not logged on.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Prior to Windows Vista, services installed as an "interactive service" could interact with Windows desktop and show a graphical user interface.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] In Windows Vista, however, interactive services are deprecated and may not operate properly, as a result of Windows Service hardening.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The command-line tool to manage Windows services is sc.exe.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] It is available for all versions of Windows NT.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] This utility is included with Windows XP and later and also in ReactOS.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The `sc` command's scope of management is restricted to the local computer.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] However, starting with Windows Server 2003, not only can `sc` do all that the Services snap-in does, but it can also install and uninstall services.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The `sc` command duplicates some features of the `net` command.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The ReactOS version was developed by Ged Murphy and is licensed under the GPL.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The following example enumerates the status for active services & drivers.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The following example displays the status for the Windows Event log service.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Windows also includes components that can do a subset of what the snap-in, Sc.exe and PowerShell do.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] The `net` command can start, stop, pause or resume a Windows service.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] In Windows Vista and later, Windows Task Manager can show a list of installed services and start or stop them.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] MSConfig can enable or disable (see startup type description above) Windows services.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] Windows services are installed and removed via *.INF setup scripts by *SetupAPI*; an installed service can be started immediately following its installation, and a running service can be stopped before its deinstallation.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] For a program to run as a Windows service, the program needs to be written to handle service start, stop, and pause messages from the Service Control Manager (SCM) through the System Services API.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] SCM is the Windows component responsible for managing service processes.
[src:windows-services/windows-service] `Sc.exe` allows new services to be installed, started, stopped and uninstalled.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler can be compared to cron or anacron on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] This service should not be confused with the scheduler, which is a core component of the OS kernel that allocates CPU resources to processes already running.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler 1.0 is included with Windows NT 4.0 (with Internet Explorer 4.0 or later), Windows 2000, Windows XP and Windows Server 2003.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] It runs as a Windows Service, and the task definitions and schedules are stored in binary `.job` files.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Tasks are manipulated directly by manipulating the `.job` files.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] On Windows 95 (with Internet Explorer 4.0 or later), Windows 98 and Windows Me, the Task Scheduler runs as an ordinary program, `mstask.exe`.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] It also displays a status icon in the notification area on Windows 95 and Windows 98 and runs as a hidden service on Windows Me, but can be made to show a tray icon.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Computer programs and scripts can access the service through six COM interfaces.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Microsoft provides a scheduling agent DLL, a sample VBScript and a configuration file to automate Task Scheduler.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] In addition to the graphical user interface for Task Scheduler in Control Panel, Windows provides two command-line tools for managing scheduled task: `at.exe` (deprecated) and `schtasks.exe`.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] However, `at.exe` cannot access tasks created or modified by Control Panel or `schtasks.exe`.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Also, tasks created with `at.exe`are not interactive by default; interactivity needs to be explicitly requested.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The binary ".job" files which the AT command produces are stored in the %WINDIR%\Tasks directory.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler 2.0 was introduced with Windows Vista and included in Windows Server 2008 as well.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The redesigned Task Scheduler user interface is now based on Management Console.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] In addition to running tasks on scheduled times or specified intervals, Task Scheduler 2.0 also supports calendar and event-based triggers, such as starting a task when a particular event is logged to the *event log*, or when a combination of events has occurred.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Also, several tasks that are triggered by the same event can be configured to run either simultaneously or in a pre-determined chained sequence of a series of actions, instead of having to create multiple scheduled tasks.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Tasks can also be configured to run based on system status such as being idle for a pre-configured amount of time, on startup, logoff, or only during or for a specified time.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] XPath expressions can be used to filter events from the Windows Event Log.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Tasks can also be delayed for a specified time after the triggering event has occurred, or repeat until some other event occurs.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Actions that need to be done if a task fails can also be configured.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The actions that can be taken in response to triggers, both event-based as well as time-based, not only include launching applications but also take a number of custom actions.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler includes a number of actions built-in, spanning a number of applications; including send an e-mail, show a message box, or fire a COM handler when it is triggered.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Custom actions can also be specified using the Task Scheduler API.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler keeps a history log of all execution details of all the tasks.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Windows Vista uses Task Scheduler 2.0 to run various system-level tasks; consequently, the Task Scheduler service can no longer be disabled (except with a simple registry tweak).
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Task Scheduler 2.0 exposes an API to allow computer programs and scripts create tasks.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The Windows API does not, however, include a managed wrapper for Task Scheduler though an open source implementation exists.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The job files for Task Scheduler 2.0 are XML-based, and are human-readable, conforming to the *Task Scheduler Schema*.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The Task Scheduler service works by managing *Tasks*; *Task* refers to the action (or actions) taken in response to trigger(s).
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] A task is defined by associating a set of actions, which can include launching an application or taking some custom-defined action, to a set of triggers, which can either be time-based or event-based.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] In addition, a task also can contain metadata that defines how the actions will be executed, such as the security context the task will run in.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Tasks are serialized to `.job` files and are stored in the special folder titled *Task Folder*, organized in subdirectories.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Programmatically, the task folder is accessed using the `ITaskFolder` interface or the `TaskFolder` scripting object and individual tasks using the `IRegisteredTask` interface or `RegisteredTask` object.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] The Last Result column displays a completion code.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] On Windows 2000 and Windows XP, when a computer is prepared for disk imaging with the sysprep utility, it cannot run tasks configured to run in the context of the SYSTEM account.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Sysprep changes the security identifier (SID) to avoid duplication but does not update scheduled tasks to use the new SID.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Consequently, the affected tasks fail to run.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] There is no solution for this problem but one may reschedule the affected tasks to work around the issue.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] On Windows Vista or Windows Server 2008, the next execution time displayed in Task Scheduler may be wrong.
[src:windows-services/windows-task-scheduler] Microsoft issued a hotfix to remedy this issue.
